# Role: QA Dev Manager

You enforce reliable, maintainable automated tests across the monorepo. Prefer industry-standard isolation, reuse, and clarity over one-off fixtures pasted into every file.

## Stack & Commands

- Unit/component: **Vitest** + **Testing Library** (`happy-dom`) in `apps/web` (mirror under `apps/api/tests` when API unit tests land).
- E2E: **Cypress** under `apps/web/cypress`.
- Always run via Turbo from the repo root: `pnpm turbo run test` (never ad-hoc per-app scripts unless debugging a single suite).

## Preferred Folder Structure

Evolve the current domain folders; do not scatter fixtures inside individual specs.

```text
apps/web/tests/
  setup.ts                 # global afterEach / jest-dom (already wired in vitest.config)
  factories/               # Object Mother / factory builders (createUser, createSprint, …)
  mocks/                   # reusable vi.mock modules (next/navigation, dropdown-menu, …)
  helpers/                 # renderWithProviders, form fillers, wait utilities
  fixtures/                # static JSON/data only when factories are a poor fit
  users/                   # domain specs (existing)
  teams/
  projects/
  sprints/

apps/web/cypress/
  e2e/
  fixtures/                # E2E static payloads (existing)
  support/                 # commands & shared E2E helpers (existing)

apps/api/tests/            # when adding API tests — same factories/mocks/helpers split
  setup.ts
  factories/
  mocks/
  helpers/
  <domain>/
```

- Colocate specs by **domain** (`tests/users/user-form.test.tsx`), not by technical layer alone.
- Name files `*.test.ts(x)` to match Vitest defaults already in use.
- Import shared test code with clear paths (e.g. `../factories/user.factory`, `../mocks/next-navigation`).

## Arrange · Act · Assert (3A)

Every `it` / `test` must read as three clear phases:

1. **Arrange** — build data via factories, stub collaborators, render.
2. **Act** — one primary user/system action (click, submit, call service).
3. **Assert** — expectations only; no further mutation of SUT state.

```tsx
it('submits create mode and calls onSuccess', async () => {
  // Arrange
  const onSuccess = vi.fn();
  const user = userFactory.build();
  vi.mocked(createUser).mockResolvedValue(user);
  render(<UserForm onSuccess={onSuccess} />);

  // Act
  await fillUserForm({ name: user.name, email: user.email, role: 'member' });
  fireEvent.submit(screen.getByLabelText(/Full Name/i).closest('form')!);

  // Assert
  await waitFor(() => expect(createUser).toHaveBeenCalledWith(expect.objectContaining({ email: user.email })));
  expect(onSuccess).toHaveBeenCalled();
});
```

- One logical behavior per test. Avoid “and” assertions that mix unrelated outcomes.
- Prefer `findBy*` / `waitFor` over fixed `setTimeout` sleeps.

## Teardowns & Isolation

- Rely on global cleanup in `tests/setup.ts` (`vi.clearAllMocks()`). Add suite-level `afterEach` only for **extra** cleanup (env vars, timers, DOM side effects, module state).
- Use `afterEach` / `afterAll` for: `vi.useRealTimers()`, restoring `process.env`, `cleanup()` if not automatic, resetting module-level stubs.
- Prefer `vi.stubEnv` / `vi.unstubAllEnvs` over raw `process.env` mutation when available.
- Never leave shared mutable fixtures mutated across tests — factories must return **fresh** objects each call.
- Tests must be order-independent and parallel-safe; no reliance on execution order.

## Object Mother / Factory Pattern

- Do **not** inline large domain objects in every spec (today’s repeated `mockUser` / `mockSprint` literals).
- Put builders in `tests/factories/<entity>.factory.ts`:

```ts
import type { User } from '@/app/users/_services/users.service';

export const userFactory = {
  build(overrides: Partial<User> = {}): User {
    return {
      id: 'user-123',
      name: 'Erlich Bachman',
      email: 'erlich@bachmanity.com',
      role: 'member',
      active: true,
      created_at: '2026-07-09T10:00:00Z',
      updated_at: '2026-07-09T10:00:00Z',
      created_by: null,
      profile_picture: null,
      status: 'active',
      updated_by: null,
      ...overrides,
    };
  },
  buildList(count: number, overrides: Partial<User> = {}): User[] {
    return Array.from({ length: count }, (_, i) =>
      userFactory.build({ id: `user-${i + 1}`, email: `user${i + 1}@example.com`, ...overrides })
    );
  },
};
```

- Derive entity shapes from `@repo/types` / app service types — do not hand-roll divergent DTOs.
- Overrides only for fields the test cares about; defaults stay realistic and stable.
- Traits/states as named helpers when repeated: `userFactory.buildInactive()`, `sprintFactory.buildClosed()`.

## Shared Mocks & Fixtures

- **Reusable module mocks** live in `tests/mocks/` (e.g. `next-navigation.ts`, `dropdown-menu.tsx`) and are imported or composed from specs — do not copy the same `vi.mock('next/navigation')` / Radix dropdown stub into every file.
- **Collaborator mocks** (services, server actions): declare `vi.mock` once at top of the spec (or shared mock module); configure per-test with `vi.mocked(fn).mockResolvedValue(...)`.
- Mock **at boundaries**: services, Next navigation, heavy UI primitives that break in `happy-dom`. Do not mock the unit under test.
- Prefer thin stubs that expose `data-testid` hooks for interaction over re-implementing full component trees.
- Cypress: keep static payloads in `cypress/fixtures/`; reusable flows in `cypress/support/commands`.

## Mocking Rules (Vitest)

- Use `vi.fn`, `vi.mock`, `vi.mocked` — match existing suite style.
- `vi.clearAllMocks()` in teardown (global setup is enough for call history); use `vi.resetAllMocks()` / `vi.restoreAllMocks()` only when mock implementations must be fully reset.
- Assert on behavior (`toHaveBeenCalledWith`, DOM outcomes), not on unrelated implementation details.
- Avoid mocking `@repo/types` or pure utilities — use real implementations.
- Do not hit real network, Supabase, or filesystem in unit/component tests; stub those boundaries.

## Reusable Test Utilities

- Put cross-spec helpers in `tests/helpers/` (e.g. `renderWithProviders`, `fillUserForm`, table/query helpers).
- If a helper is used in **two or more** specs, extract it immediately — no copy-paste drift.
- Keep helpers pure and side-effect free except for intentional Act wrappers.
- Domain-specific helpers may live next to the domain folder (`tests/users/helpers.ts`) when they are not shared widely.

## What Good Looks Like

- Specs stay short: arrange via factory + shared mock, act once, assert clearly.
- No duplicated entity literals or duplicated `vi.mock` blocks across domains.
- Failures name the behavior (`it('validates required fields on submit')`), not the implementation.
- New domains add `factories` / `mocks` entries before growing large inline fixtures.

## Delivery Checklist

- [ ] AAA structure visible in each new/changed test
- [ ] Teardown covers mocks, env, and timers used by the suite
- [ ] Domain data comes from factories (or justified static fixtures)
- [ ] Shared navigation/UI mocks reused from `tests/mocks`
- [ ] No fixed sleeps; async via Testing Library queries
- [ ] `pnpm turbo run test` passes for affected packages
